social_posts.post_text: good at making you bad at eye contact

Out here giving live, love, laugh.

I’ve gotten a few remarks about weight loss lately and while I understand no malice is intended in the remark I do not accept criticism or compliments about any changes in my weight. So when you mention I seem different just know that it’s the people in my life that make me grin like an idiot and learning to stop letting what I look like in photos turn me off from being in them.

If anyone needs me, I’ll be over here still endlessly impressed with myself whenever I overcome things I never even dreamt of attempting.

I’m sure some of you are sick of hearing about it because I talk about it so often but being in an emotionally abusive relationship when I was so young still shapes a lot of my experiences today. I was told repeatedly that if he never amounted to anything remarkable it would be because he stayed with me. He often said he would be stuck in our hometown forever because I was destined for nothing special. 

It has taken years (and requires me to still actively work at it) plus I still cry every time I do something cool or think about it too much, but I’m getting there. 

I set (and fucking accomplished) my goals of trying to surf and to also build my endurance enough to the point where doing a moderate hike didn’t leave me breathless. Both of which left me happy crying in the ocean, on the beach, atop a lookout and sitting on a rock. 🥹
Feels like a thong-shaped tan line was inevitable / maybe I just wanted everyone to see my fresh wax.

social_posts.post_text: #leoseasonsupremacy

If you’re a creator who shares toxic content along the lines of “people ask me how I get to eat so much and stay thin” to flex your workout routine then maybe you need to need to rethink your relationship with food. 

We get to meet amazing chefs and try exceptional dishes and one of the biggest takeaways I get from these experiences is that food does not hold morality.

What you’re doing is applauding thinness and demonizing anyone who isn’t because “if you can do it, why cant they?” It’s always straight-sized creators talking about how they “stay lean” while not acknowledging what an immense privilege is it to have the funds and the time to commit to fitness classes - another thing that is often gifted to us in exchange for posting content. 

Also major side eyes to these studios that partner with creators to perpetuate the message that movement is a punishment that gets rewarded with sustenance. Your clients who actually pay for a membership to be there deserve to not be mislead into the belief that calories are something you have to earn through suffering. 

This shouldn’t be a hot take, but don’t follow foodie accounts who make you feel worse about your relationship with food.

Getting #OutThere with @kathmandu_outdoor 🍄

What a unique experience of doing an educational forest walk while product testing new gear followed by a pop-up sauna and cold plunge. Moments like this are a nice time for me to reflect on how I don’t have to do it, I get to do it.

I wouldn’t say I’m outdoorsy, but I am outsidesy. 

Do I want to go camping? Probably not. But do I want to go sit in a park? Absolutely. A strenuous hike? Maybe but only if there’s snacks involved. A nature walk? Sign me up. 

I was initially surprised when @kathmandu_outdoor invited me on their outdoor excursion earlier this week but chatting with the team reassured me that not all outdoor adventures need to be about reaching the highest summit but rather enjoying being in nature. 

What’s your favourite way to get outsidesy (or outdoorsy)?

#OutThere 📸: @spencerwatson.ca

Yesterday my social anxiety almost got the best of me and I really had to fight the urge not to cancel all of my commitments to just stay at home to avoid meeting new people. Because my job requires such a high social battery I’m also able to use it as common ground when at industry events because we can always default to talking about work so in non-work settings I tend to feel a bit out of place. 

Something I learned in therapy about myself is that my anxiety convinces me that people feel “obligated” to share their time and energy with me and I’m still learning how to grasp the belief that people enjoy my company. 

Small things that helped me through the day: getting messages from new friends asking if I would attending events I was anxious about going to, an impromptu get together with my best friends and a surprise text of gratitude. 

I spend so much time worried that people are thinking the worst about me that I never stop to consider they might think highly of me. Grateful for all the little things that could help motivate me to show up and experience moments like this. ❤️

Aspiring pilates princess 👸🏻

Video from @zaleskajewelry x @lagreewest class hosted by @sylvia.tennant , taught by @bouse.fulton

Anyone else feeling like we’re really just crawling towards the new year? Like this past month I have not been able to get into the Christmas spirit at all. At the top of the month I hit the worse slump I’ve had in years. I’m talking laying in bed and not eating for days, something just washed over me and I felt so much dread. I was constantly on the verge of tears and being around people I felt safe around was almost too intimidating because I could feel my vulnerability start to peek through. 

As I started to ebb and flow out of that tenderness I was then hit with a career blow which leaves me wondering what’s next while also learning a new word; catastrophizing. When things don’t go accordingly to plan I ended up on step 18 of the worse case scenario.

Recently in a @gvillasenor class she said something that really resonated with me. She was talking about experimenting with different levels of workout intensities but the words have stuck with me the past few days. “What’s the best that could happen?”

I have to believe what is meant for me will not pass me by and at the end of the day it’ll be okay. If things aren’t okay right now, that’s also okay - it’s not the end of the day yet. 

Anyways, what kind of photo do you even use for a caption like this? I suppose this photo of me on top of a mountain is some kind of beautiful metaphor about going through difficulty to reach the summit but what I like best about this photo is how happy I was that day. A reminder that I have to hold the messy parts of being a human with the fun and beautiful parts too. And that a bad day, week or month doesn’t mean it’s a bad life.

social_posts.post_text:
Any room on the 2023 recap bandwagon for me? 😛

But for real, I love seeing all of y’alls recaps. What a privilege it is to witness the big moments and the small moments, the milestones and the mundane.

Thank you for being here through the celebrations, grief, new discoveries and heartache. While there was a lot of difficult moments this past year there were a lot of beautiful ones too. 2023 was the 10 year mark of living in Vancouver and what a decade it has been. I often remark that I can close my eyes and picture what my life would have looked like if I never left my hometown but that version of me would never be able to imagine what life turned out to be. I moved here without knowing anyone here and now my life is full of love, adventure and new experiences.
